\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 The way you edit a file within MicroEMACS is by first reading it into a {\ul buffer}{\v\ul Buffer}, altering it and then saving it. Therefore, the most commonly used {\ul commands}{\v Command} to access files are:

\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul ^X^F}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb find-file}{\v find_file}\tab to read a file from disk for editing
\par \pard \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \tab {\ul ^X^S}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb save-file}{\v save_file}\tab to save an edited file to disk
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Other read commands are:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul ^X^I}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb insert-file}{\v insert_file}\tab to insert at the {\ul point}{\v Point}
\par \tab {\ul ^X^R}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb read-file}{\v read_file}\tab to replace the whole buffer contents
\par \pard \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \tab {\ul ^X^V}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb view-file}{\v view_file}\tab to read for viewing, preventing any alterations
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 To save a buffer to another file than the one MicroEMACS would normally access, use:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul ^X^W}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb write-file}{\v write_file}\tab to overwrite the file's previous contents
\par \pard \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \tab {\ul ^X^A}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb append-file}{\v append_file}\tab to append to the end of the file
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Searching and Replacing}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} SearchingAndReplacing}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Procedures:030}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} search;replace}}
 Searching and Replacing
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Commands for searching for and replacing strings come in a number of different flavors. The simplest {\ul command}{\v Command} is:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul ^S}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb search-forward}{\v search_forward}
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Following that, you can search for yet another occurrence of the same string by using:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul A-S}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb hunt-forward}{\v\uldb hunt_forward}
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 You can also search towards the beginning of the file instead of towards the end by using:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul ^R}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb search-reverse}{\v\uldb search_reverse}
\par \pard \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \tab {\ul A-R}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb hunt-backward}{\v\uldb hunt_backward}
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 To replace strings, use:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul M-R}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb replace-string}{\v\uldb replace_string}\tab to replace all occurrences
\par \pard \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \tab {\ul M-^R}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb query-replace-string}{\v\uldb query_replace_string}\tab to get queried for each replacement{\uldb 
\par }\pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 MicroEMACS also supports incremental searching:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-3600\li3600\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx3600 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul ^XS}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb incremental-search}{\v incremental_search}\tab towards the beginning
\par \pard \s3\fi-3600\li3600\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx3600 \tab {\ul ^XR}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb reverse-incremental-search}{\v reverse_incremental_search}\tab towards the end
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Cutting and Pasting}}{\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} CuttingAndPasting}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Procedures:040}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K}
 cut;paste;move;kill;copy;clipboard}} Cutting and Pasting
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 MicroEMACS allows you to manipulate text by blocks of any size. You can {\uldb copy}{\v CopyingText} or {\uldb mov}{\uldb e}{\v MovingText} text within MicroEMACS through the {\ul kill buffer}{\v\ul KillBuffer}.

\par Under Microsoft Windows, you can also exchange text with other Windows applications via the {\ul clipboard}{\v Clipboard}, using the {\uldb cut-region}{\v\uldb cut_region}, {\uldb clip-region}{\v\uldb clip_region} and {\uldb insert-clip}{\v\uldb 
insert_clip} commands.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Moving Text}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #}
 MovingText}}{\fs16\up6  +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} CuttingAndPasting:movingtext}}{\fs16\up6  }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} move}}{\fs16\up6  }Moving Text

\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 To move text from one place to another:
\par \pard\plain \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 \f2\fs20\lang1033 1.\tab Move to the beginning of the text you want to move.
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 2.\tab Set the {\ul mark}{\v\ul Mark} there with the {\uldb set-mark}{\v\uldb set_mark} ({\ul M- }{\v Keystroke}) command.
\par 3.\tab Move the {\ul point}{\v\ul Point} to the end of the text.
\par 4.\tab Use the {\uldb kill-region}{\v\uldb kill_region} ({\ul ^W}{\v Keystroke}) command to delete the {\ul region}{\v region} you just defined. The text will be saved in the {\ul kill buffer}{\v\uldb KillBuffer}.
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 5.\tab Move the point to the place you want the text to appear.
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 6.\tab Use the {\uldb yank}{\v yank} ({\ul ^Y}{\v Keystroke}) command to copy the text from the kill buffer to the current point.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Repeat steps 5 and 6 to insert more copies of the same text.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Copying Text}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #}
 CopyingText}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} CuttingAndPasting:copyingtext}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} copy}} Copying Text
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 To copy text from one place to another:
\par \pard\plain \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 \f2\fs20\lang1033 1.\tab Move to the beginning of the text you want to copy.
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 2.\tab Set the {\ul mark}{\v\ul Mark} there with the {\uldb set-mark}{\v\uldb set_mark} ({\ul M- }{\v Keystroke}) command.
\par 3.\tab Move the {\ul point}{\v\ul Point} to the end of the text.
\par 4.\tab Use the {\uldb copy-region}{\v copy_region} ({\ul M-W}{\v Keystroke}) command to copy the {\ul region}{\v Region} to the {\ul kill buffer}{\v\uldb KillBuffer}.
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 5.\tab Move the point to the place you want the text to appear.
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 6.\tab Use the {\uldb yank}{\v yank} ({\ul ^Y}{\v Keystroke}) command to copy the text from the kill buffer to the current point.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Repeat steps 5 and 6 to insert more copies of the same text.
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Using the Mouse}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #}
 UsingTheMouse}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Procedures:050}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} mouse}} Using the Mouse
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 MicroEMACS can use the mouse to perform many basic editing tasks. Unless mouse behavior has been altered by a {\ul macro}{\v Macro}, you can perform the following actions:
\par \pard\plain \s11\li360\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\uldb Copying a Region}{\v CopyARegion}
\par {\uldb Killing a Region}{\v KillARegion}
\par {\uldb Moving a Mode Line}{\v MovingAModeLine}
\par {\uldb Pasting Text}{\v PastingText}
\par {\uldb Repositioning the Point}{\v RepositioningThePoint}
\par \pard \s11\li360\sa120\tx2880 {\uldb Scrolling Text Inside a Window}{\v ScrollingTextInsideAWindow}
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Repositioning the Point with the Mouse}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} RepositioningThePoint}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} UsingTheMouse:repositioningthepoint}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 K} position;point;mouse}} Repositioning the Point with the Mouse
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Move the mouse to where you want the {\ul point}{\v Point} to be, and click once with the left mouse button and release. The point will move there, making any {\ul screen}{\v Screen} or {\ul window}{\v Window}
 active to do so.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Scrolling Text Inside a Window with the Mouse}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} ScrollingTextInsideAWindow}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} UsingTheMouse:scrollingtextinsideawindow}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 
{\fs16\up6 K} scroll;mouse}} Scrolling Text Inside a Window with the Mouse
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Position the mouse on the text to drag, press the left button, move the mouse to where to display the text (horizontally or vertically), and release the mouse button.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 If you are using the {\uldb CUA.CMD}{\v CUA.CMD} {\ul page}{\v\ul Page} (which is usually the case under Microsoft Windows), the above action is performed by pressing the {\b right} mouse button instead of the left one.
\par Note that if you drag diagonally and the {\uldb $diagflag}{\v _diagflag} {\ul variable}{\v Variable} is set to FALSE (the default value), the text will move only in the vertical direction.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Moving a Mode Line with the Mouse}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 
{\fs16\up6 #} MovingAModeLine}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} UsingTheMouse:movingamodeline}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} mode line;mouse}}
 Moving a Mode Line with the Mouse
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Position the mouse on a {\ul mode line}{\v ModeLine} (except the bottom one which cannot be moved), press the left button, move to another position and release the button. The mode line will move, resizing the {\ul 
windows}{\v Window} which are above and below. 
\par If you are using the {\uldb CUA.CMD}{\v CUA.CMD} {\ul page}{\v\ul Page} (which is usually the case under Microsoft Windows), the above action is performed by pressing the {\b right} mouse button instead of the left one.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Copying a Region with the Mouse}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} CopyARegion}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} UsingTheMouse:copyingaregion}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} copy;region;mouse}}
 Copying a Region with the Mouse
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Position the mouse at the beginning of the text to be copied, press the right button, move the mouse to the other end of the text, release the button. This actually makes the selected text the current {\ul region}{
\v Region} and then copies it into the {\ul kill buffer}{\v KillBuffer}.
\par If you are using the {\uldb CUA.CMD}{\v CUA.CMD} {\ul page}{\v\ul Page} (which is usually the case under Microsoft Windows), the above action is performed by pressing the {\b Shift }key and the {\b right}
 mouse button together instead of just the right mouse button.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Killing a Region with the Mouse}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} KillARegion}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} UsingTheMouse:killingaregion}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} kill;delete;region;mouse}}
 Killing a Region with the Mouse
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 After {\uldb copying a region}{\v CopyARegion}, without moving the mouse, click the right mouse button once. The text will be deleted, but it will still be kept in the {\ul kill buffer}{\v KillBuffer}. 
\par If you are using the {\uldb CUA.CMD}{\v CUA.CMD} {\ul page}{\v\ul Page} (which is usually the case under Microsoft Windows), the above action is performed by pressing the {\b Shift }key and the {\b right}
 mouse button together instead of just the right mouse button.
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Pasting Text with the Mouse}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 #} PastingText}} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} UsingTheMouse:pastingtext}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} paste;mouse}}
 Pasting Text with the Mouse
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Move anywhere away from the place the mouse was last clicked, and click the right button once. The last text placed in the {\ul kill buffer}{\v KillBuffer} will be inserted there.
\par If you are using the {\uldb CUA.CMD}{\v CUA.CMD} {\ul page}{\v\ul Page} (which is usually the case under Microsoft Windows), the above action is performed by pressing the {\b Shift }key and the {\b right} mouse button together instead of just the right
 mouse button.
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\lang1033 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Using Menus}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} UsingMenus}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Procedures:060}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} menu}}
 Using menus
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Under Microsoft Windows, MicroEMACS sports an extensive menu system. Menu items can point to a pop-up menu or directly invoke a {\ul command}{\v Command} or a {\ul macro}{\v Macro}
. A few menu items are not linked to any MicroEMACS commands or macro (for instance, the "{\ul A}bout..." item in the "{\ul H}elp" menu).
\par \pard \s6\sa120 The text of each menu item can contain the following hints:
\par \pard\plain \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab Items that lead to the apparition of a dialog box are followed by an ellipsis "{\b ...}".
\par \pard \s8\fi-360\li360\sa120\tx360\tx1440\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320 \tab Items that require the user to type additional information in the {\ul message line}{\v MessageLine} are followed by a colon "{\b :}".
\par \tab Items that require a {\ul numeric argument}{\v Argument} are preceded by an equal sign "{\b =}".
\par \tab Items that are equivalent to a key {\ul binding}{\v Binding} have the corresponding key sequence displayed on the right side of the menu.
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 The MicroEMACS menus can be {\uldb modified}{\v CustomizingMenus} by {\uldb macros}{\v MacroLanguage} to add/remove menus or menu items. The initial menus on the menu bar are:
\par \pard\plain \s11\li360\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\uldb File}{\v FileMenu}
\par {\uldb Edit}{\v EditMenu}
\par {\uldb Search}{\v SearchMenu}
\par {\uldb Execute}{\v ExecuteMenu}
\par {\uldb Mis}{\uldb cellaneous}{\v MiscellaneousMenu}
\par {\uldb Screen}{\v ScreenMenu}
\par \pard \s11\li360\sa120\tx2880 {\uldb Help}{\v HelpMenu}
\par \pard\plain \s252\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 \page ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} File menu}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #}
 FileMenu}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} UsingMenus:050}} File menu
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb menu}{\v UsingMenus} contains the following items:
\par \pard\plain \s2\fi-2520\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Open...\tab invokes the {\uldb find-file}{\v find_file} command. If the {\uldb MDI.CMD}{\v MDI.CMD} {\ul page}{\v Page} is loaded, this menu item is modified and {\ul bound}{\v Binding} to the 
{\uldb open-file}{\v open_file} {\ul macro}{\v Macro}
\par View...\tab invokes the {\uldb view-file}{\v view_file} command
\par Insert...\tab invokes the {\uldb insert-file}{\v insert_file} command
\par Read over...\tab invokes the {\uldb read-file}{\v read_file} command
\par Rename...\tab invokes the {\uldb change-file-name}{\v change_file_name} command
\par Save\tab invokes the {\uldb save-file}{\v save_file} command
\par Save as...\tab invokes the {\uldb write-file}{\v write_file} command
\par Append...\tab invokes the {\uldb append-file}{\v append_file} command
\par Encryption key :\tab invokes the {\uldb set-encryption-key}{\v set_encryption_key} command
\par {\uldb Buffer}{\v BufferSubmenu}\tab submenu
\par {\uldb Window}{\v WindowSubmenu}\tab submenu
\par Mode...\tab brings up a dialog box to change the {\uldb modes of operation}{\v ModesOfOperation} for the current {\ul buffer}{\v Buffer}.
\par Global mode...\tab brings up a dialog box to change the {\uldb global modes of operation}{\v ModesOfOperation}.
\par Save + exit\tab invokes the {\uldb quick-exit}{\v quick_exit} command
\par Exit\tab invokes the {\uldb exit-emacs}{\v exit_emacs} command
\par \pard\plain \s251\sa120\tx2880 \b\f2\fs20\lang1033 {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 \page ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Buffer submenu}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 
#} BufferSubmenu}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} FileMenu:050}} Buffer submenu
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 This {\uldb menu}{\v UsingMenus} is accessed via the {\uldb File menu}{\v FileMenu}. It contains the following items:
\par \pard\plain \s2\fi-2520\li2880\sa120\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Next\tab invokes the {\uldb next-buffer}{\v next_buffer} command
\par Select :\tab invokes the {\uldb select-buffer}{\v select_buffer} command
\par Unmark\tab invokes the {\uldb unmark-buffer}{\v unmark_buffer} command
\par Rename :\tab invokes the {\uldb name-buffer}{\v name_buffer} command
\par Delete :\tab invokes the {\uldb delete-buffer}{\v delete_buffer} command
\par Narrow to region\tab invokes the {\uldb narrow}{\uldb -to-region}{\v narrow_to_region} command
