\par Window\tab Pane
\par \pard \s11\li360\sa120\tx2880 Screen\tab Window
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 Each screen has its own set of {\uldb windows}{\v Windows}. Switching from one screen to another (for instance by clicking on that screen) will preserve the window setup, the colors and the {\ul buffers}{\v Buffer}
 being displayed.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 When MicroEMACS starts up, it displays a single screen named "MAIN". Extra screens can be created by the command:
\par \pard\plain \s3\fi-2880\li2880\sa120\tqr\tx720\tx900\tx2880 \f2\fs20\lang1033 \tab {\ul A-F}{\v Keystroke}\tab {\uldb find-screen}{\v find_screen}
\par \pard\plain \s253\sa240\tx2880 \b\f2\cf2\lang1033 {\fs16 \page }{\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Windows}}{\fs16  }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} Windows}
} {\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} Procedures:150}} {\plain \f2\fs16\up6\lang1033 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f2\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} window}} Windows
\par \pard\plain \s6\sa120 \f2\fs20\lang1033 MicroEMACS uses windows to display and allow you to edit the contents of {\ul buffers}{\v Buffer}. A single {\ul screen}{\v Screen} will show one or more windows, separated by a {\ul mode line}{\v ModeLine}
 which describes the contents of the window above it.
\par \pard \s6\sa120 You can scroll text vertically and horizontally within a window by using the arrow keys or the page-up, page-down, home and end keys. Note that if a line of text extends beyond the boundary of a window, a dollar "{\b $}" sign is 
displayed instead of the last visible character.
